Observed and recorded (in two segments) a White-eyed vireo mimicking the call notes of a Great Crested flycatcher, which has *not* yet returned to this territory for the summer. When I first began to observe it, the WEVI produced the mimic call notes between a series of typical "SKIP-to-my-LOU-lou" phrases. This recording captured its pattern of "SKIP-to-my-LOU-Lou" phrase followed by two straight mimic notes. Following this series, the same WEVI mimicked five straight GCFL call notes over 36 seconds [XC403847] before repeating another typical "SKIP-to-my-LOU-Lou" phrase.

Following a series of typical "SKIP-to-my-LOU-lou" phrases (between which were included two straight call notes mimicking Great Crested flycatcher) [XC403848], this same WEVI mimicked five straight GCFL call notes over 36 seconds before repeating another typical "SKIP-to-my-LOU-Lou" phrase. This recording captured four of those five mimic call notes.

Editing: High-pass filter, cutoff frequency 1kHz, some amplification.

Equipment: Olympus WS-822 digital recorder with Audio-technica ATR 6550 shotgun.

Natural sound. Bird singing from lower branches of a tree just inside the forest edge at the NW corner of the grounds. Switches song type during the recording.

#Habitat#
29-acre estate centrally located in Oxford, MS consisting of antebellum home surrounded by lawns and adjacent forest. Privet hedges and small thickets divide the grounds into distinct lawn units. Bordered on all sides by mature oak-hickory forest. Forest edge consists of oak spp, hickory spp, red cedar, mulberry, with understory along the edge dominated by privet (Ligustrum sp.). Grounds around the house include isolated trees and manicured hedges. A path from the end of the parking area leads northward ~1 km through the forest to the northern edge of the property abutting the University of Mississippi campus

#Editing#
Edited in Adobe Audition. Butterworth high-pass filter, order 3, cutoff frequency 800 Hz

#Equipment#
Fostex FR-2 digital recorder with Sennheiser microphone and Telinga pro 22" parabolic reflector.

#Habitat#
State waterfowl refuge along the margins of USACE flood control reservoir. Strip along the lake margins ~1km wide of moist soil grassland with mix of forbs, native warm season grasses (Andropogon, Schyzachyrium, Eragrostis, Aristida, etc.), and some sparse woody vegetation (Cephalanthus, Quercus saplings, etc.) bounded by oak hickory forest and, in places, pine plantation.  Three or four shallow waterfowl impoundments partially flooded in the winter.

#Editing#

#Equipment#

recordings.loc: Pueblo Canyon, Los Alamos, Los Alamos County, New Mexico
recordings.rmk: The bird was not seen, and this recording was made in essentially the same location as previously reported by Steve Fettig and Mouser Williams, both of whom also got images of the bird.  The recording has only been trimmed in length to isolate the bird of interest.  Also in the recording is the repeated song of the Spotted Towhee.  For comparison to what very well may be the same bird, see this site for Mouser Williams.
Song repeats three times in recording, heard from canopy approx 15m high, near to salt-marshes.

This recording has not been modified except to remove the recordist voice-over at the end. The recording was taken at Rowan Oak in Oxford, MS which is an antebellum home surrounded by lawns bordered by 25 acres of oak-hickory forest. Much of the grounds is bordered by unpruned privet (*Ligustrum*). Singing was in progress when the recording began. Ten songs are represented in the recording. A description of the recording with some statistics can be found here: https://sites.google.com/site/oxfordnhc/field-reports/listeningtowhite-eyedvireos.

The bird moved back and forth over a distance of approximately 10m during the recording and was always within 10m of the recorder, at times as close as 2-3m. At times it would perch in one place for several minutes while singing. At other points it would move through the brush rarely singing from the same perch twice. The recording was terminated when the bird paused for more than 30 sec. I have listed the quality as B primarily because of the cicada noise at lower frequencies.
